<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.thecouriermail.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,5936,5767964%255E954,00.html">China steps up astronaut planning!</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.thecouriermail.news.com.au/common/imagedata/0,1658,227754,00.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
Shenzhou IV.<br>
<br>
31dec02<br>
CHINA'S fourth unmanned space capsule blasted into orbit early yesterday in a test launch that could soon lead to manned flight.<br>
<br>
The official Xinhua News Agency said the Shenzhou IV spacecraft left a launch pad in the Gobi Desert and entered a preset orbit. <br>
<br>
The craft was to return to Earth later, but Xinhua did not specify when. <br>
<br>
It said the capsule carried all the equipment for manned flight and would test life support and other systems. <br>
<br>
Beijing has invested an undisclosed amount of money in its secretive, military-linked space program. A successful manned launch would make China only the third country, after Russia and the US, to send a human into space on its own. <br>
<br>
Yesterday's flight was the second Shenzhou launch in 10 months – the shortest period yet between capsule test flights and a possible sign of growing Chinese confidence. <br>
<br>
It &quot;laid a solid foundation for the country's future task of sending Chinese astronauts to outer space&quot;, Xinhua said, and &quot;could soon lead to its (China's) manned space voyage&quot;. <br>
<br>
China launched its first Shenzhou capsule, whose name means &quot;Sacred Vessel&quot;, in November 1999. <br>
<br>
The craft is based on Russian technology with extensive modifications by Chinese scientists. <br>
<br>
The Communist government does not announce launches in advance and has not publicly set a date for manned flight. <br>
<br>
But with official confidence growing after a series of successes, state media has indicated that astronauts could be sent up in the near future. <br>
<br>
China's No. 3 leader, Li Peng, chairman of the national legislature, was among senior officials who watched the launch in Jiuquan, Xinhua said. Others included Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo and Jia Qinglin, a member of the party's ruling Politburo Standing Committee. <br>
<br>
A corps of astronauts drawn from elite fighter pilots in China's air force has been training for several years. <br>
<br>
The third, 10-day Shenzhou flight in March carried a mannequin in a spacesuit and state media said it tested life-support equipment.AP <br>
<br>
