<br>
With some upgrading, this seemingly archaic technology could be used for a series of spectacular missions, including some that have no real precedent. This is especially true when we consider that the comparison is not really direct and that modern technologies, especially in computer systems, would greatly simplify such operations as orbital rendezvous. The Chinese program also benefits, of course, from US and Soviet experience in space.<br>
 <br>
Among the possibilities, besides the lunar landing:<br>
1. A lunar flyby in the very short term--this is possible with the current system if Earth orbit rendezvous is used for refueling <br>
2. A mission to an Earth-crossing asteroid. This actually requires less delta-v is some cases than a moon landing, and mission time would be much shorter than a planetary flight, possibly just a few days. It would also be much simpler technically than a moon landing, since a separate lander is not required. The Shenzhou itself, with the addition of a very large boost section, could do it.<br>
3. Landing on the moons of Mars. This is a potentially valuable mission that would be much easier than a landing on the planet itself since, again, a separate lander is not required. This makes a very great difference in mission requirements, since the Mars lander is inherently very large and complex and would have to be boosted all the way from Earth. This mission is the most ambitious and would require a large transit craft, along the lines of the original Salyut space station. <br>
<br>
Even a small and relatively primitive nuclear propulsion capbility, something like a &quot;minimum-NERVA&quot;, would greatly simplify any of these ideas and bring them within short-term reach, possibly on the first series of manned missions.  <br>
<br>
A clever combination of basic 60s hardware and recent innovations could easily allow for a spectacular mission that would really put the Western devils in their place. <br>
The likely reaction makes for a wonderful set of mental images: The Sputnik hysteria of 1957-58 would pale in comparison. <br>
As I have said before, there would be wailing and gnashing of teeth in Washington, Congressional investigations, demands that heads roll at NASA, and a general and very positive re-evaluation of the space program. <br>
<br>
We should do everything we can to encourage the Chinese in these endevours, it will benefit all of us.   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A> at: 12/31/02 7:11:32 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zentrander>Zentrander</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 36<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/31/02 7:47 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=673.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/zilla.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: China spaceflight</span><hr size=1> And what has the trend of the Chinese economy been?  Economics analyzes trends-and China's economy has been growing by leaps and bounds.  The next 5 years, 10 years, 20 years, this is all fairly short term.  The Chinese economy is urbanizing, and it [b]will[/b] be a world power.  <br>
