If I was to buy a block of land in the US and begin building a house on it I would be fined and perhaps arrested. The council planners would fall on me like vultures. The builders union would stone me. I would be told to pay exhorbitant fees for plans, licenses, professional construction companies, rates requests, soil tests, etc etc etc. In China I could build a house out of straw or mud brick and the Government wouldn't care a damn. Because it's my land and I can do almost anything I want with it. There are many definitions of freedom. I was not stating that China is a better country than the US. I was referring to freedom. Specifically freedom to start a space launch industry. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It is not democracy that sabotages the West's will to progress and explore, it is the influence of an anti-democratic minority of powerful authoritarian elitists within that democracy.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You are saying it is not democracy but a small number of democratic leaders. Democracy isn't some nebulous abstract thing. It is the sum of its leaders and what they are capable of doing. The Chinese are not suffering from this disease of democracy. Those who would use the public as a force of control are impotent there. The government can do as it likes. Call it evil if you like. Condemn their human rights record until the sun goes down if you must but don't think for a second anything inside China stands between the Government and any decision they might make concerning space. While the West bites its own tail and chases it around in circles the Chinese will continue to make steady progress. I honestly hope they don't become a democracy because that will destroy them and their efforts to reach space. Look at what democracy did to Russia.<br>
