That's not what I said at all. The luddite totalitarians were not elected by anyone, neither were their media cronies. They are calling the shots in terms of space exploration, however. This does not mean that the process is democratic, it is the direct opposite. The American (and Australian, btw) vision of democracy requires an informed electorate. <br>
Democracy exists only to the extent that the electorate can make informed and rational decisions. The situation today is hopeless in that regard without some fundamental changes. Fortunately, there are many signs that this fundamental change may be possible. The internet creates a medium that is beyond the control of the Hollywood/Madison Avenue Axis. <br>
<br>
The simple pressure of events is another factor. The collective corps of media pundits could not have been more wrong about the campaign in Afghanistan. I, a non-pundit and very minor media personality, predicted that the Taliban would be overwhelmed in short order. Major media conformists laughed, the standard wisdom invoked the invincible ten-foot tall Afghan mountain man, Slayer of Empires. <br>
Another example, the eco-wacky star Paul Ehrlich is famous for his discredited predictions. In 1974, he predicted that the US would be out of oil by 1980. He also predicted food rationing by 2000; instead we have a major obesity problem in this country. Yet, Ehrlich remains a major force in the eco-cult movement. Some of his followers complain about growing public apathy, oblivious to its real nature.    <br>
<br>
 It seems sometimes that these people are never held to account when they are consistently wrong, but somebody, somewhere, remembers each time it happens. The net, and other non-Axis media like talk radio, allow us to point this out. The mass medias' image of ultimate credibilty reached its height back in the 60s when the socialist fraud Walter Cronkite was the &quot;most trusted man in America&quot;. This image is eroding away to nothing, and the media-control culture is inherently unable to recognize this. <br>
<br>
The ultimate goal of space development is democratic, an unlimited frontier with unlimited opportunity. The whole idea is anathema to totalitarians. The Chinese are moving toward democracy, perhaps a better and truer democracy than the media-bound and activist-hobbled west can really imagine. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 113<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/2/03 6:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=673.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Update:manned mission announced officially</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://i.cnn.net/cnn/2003/TECH/space/01/01/china.space/story.shenzhou.ap.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
